[size=150]Short list of features[/size]


[list]
[*]Many keyboard bindings, different for Russian and English layouts ([c]RAlt + F1 toggle on/off[/c]), e.g.: [c]RAlt + A[/c] → Ă, [c]RAlt + O[/c] → Ø; [c]RAlt + Ф[/c] → Ѳ, [c]RAlt + Щ[/c] → Ҩ. Supports user-defined bindings.
[*]“Compositing” mode ([c]RAlt×2[/c]) that allows converting symbol sequences into another symbol, e.g.: [c]TH[/c] → Þ, [c]WY[/c] → Ƿ, [c]1/10[/c] → ⅒ etc. Has a tooltip with suggestions of matching sequences. Supports user-defined sequences.
[*]“Alternative modes” ([c]LWin + LAlt + S[/c]), a feature that supports the aforementioned writing systems.
[*]“Glyph variations” ([c]LWin + LAlt + A[/c]), allows typing variants of characters, e.g.: A → ᴬ𝐀𝘼𝙰𝕬𝓐 etc.
[*]“TELEX/VNI-like modes” ([c]LWin + LAlt + D[/c]), simplifies typing of Vietnamese, Jarai and Pinyin with input similar to Vietnamese Telex and VNI layouts.
[*]Switching between typing Unicode character → HTML → LaTeX command ([c]RAlt + RShift + F1[/c]), e.g.: [c]Ă[/c] → [c]&Abreve;[/c] → [c]\u{A}[/c]. Has a tooltip with suggestions of matching sequences.
[*]Search and insert symbols by “tags” ([c]LWin + LAlt + F[/c]), e.g.: prompt “plus minus” gives “±”.
[*]“Internal” keyboard layouts with support for user-defined layouts.
[*]Mini-modes for typing super/subscript ([c]LWin + LAlt + ↑/↓[/c]) digits and roman numerals ([c]LWin + LAlt + RShift + ↑[/c]).
[*]Favorites system that adds favorited symbols to the “Favorites” tab in the main GUI and shows their sequences in the “Composite“ mode tooltip.
[*]Support for modifications. For example, you are allowed to add a new “Alternative mode” with new symbols (e.g., “Old Mongolian”).
[*]And other, less significant features…
[*]GUI Windows: Lists of symbols (binds, sequences etc.) and help ([c]LWin + LAlt + Home[/c]); Glyph Variations; User-defined sequences; Mods; “Legend”; Settings ([c]RCtrl + F9[/c]) etc. All of these are available to be opened from the tray context menu.
[/list]

[size=150]Compositing mode[/size]

Inspired by the Compose key from Linux and WinCompose. Converts a sequence of symbols into something else.

Activated by double-pressing [c]RAlt[/c]. User input will be displayed in a tooltip along with matching suggestions and a list of favorite symbol recipes.


[spoiler2="Details"]

Compose mode triggers on the first exact recipe match. This is both a plus and a slight minus — such behavior won’t allow typing, for example, [c]Ǣ[/c] due to the automatic triggering of [c]AE[/c] → [c]Æ[/c]. To solve this problem, I introduced a hold mode ([c]Pause[/c] key), in which composition waits for [c]Enter[/c] to be pressed or for the hold to be released.

In addition to hold mode, you can use the grave “operator” [c] ` [/c]. It doesn’t cancel automatic triggering, but saves its result in the active composition variable instead of sending it to the application window. This allows continuing sequences if there are recipes that start with the obtained result. [c]Ǣ[/c] = [c]A`E → Æ → Æ<MACRON>[/c].

General key list:

[list]
[*][c]Enter[/c] — confirm input.
[*][c]Escape[/c] — cancel compose mode.
[*][c]Backspace[/c] — delete the last character.
[*][c]Insert[/c] — paste clipboard contents.
[*][c]Pause[/c] — toggle hold mode.
[/list]

[img]https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DemerNkardaz/DSL-KeyPad-Docs/refs/heads/main/Media/compose_demo.webp[/img]

[b]Operators[/b]

[list]
[*]Grave [c] ` [/c] — described above.
[*]([c]NUMBER[/c]) — when starting input with this operator, the recipe result will be duplicated the specified number of times, “(5) TH” → “ÞÞÞÞÞ”.
[*]([c]~[/c]) — when starting input with this operator, you can enter whole words within which recipes will be processed, “[c](~) T<COMMA>ara Roma<CIRCUMFLEX>neasca<BREVE>[/c]” → “Țara Românească“.
[*]([c]NUMBER~[/c]) — combination of the previous operators.
[*][c]##[/c] — allows preventing processing of unwanted sequences, “[c](~) tho<ACUTE>rr” → “þórr”, “(\~) t##ho<ACUTE>rr[/c]” → “thórr”.
[/list]

[b]Unicode Codepoint and Alt-code Input[/b]

Compose mode can be used to insert symbols by their codes. Input starts with U+/Ю+ or A+/А+, followed by the value. You can specify multiple values by separating them with spaces.

Alt-codes are affected by the active layout language: numbers 128–255 and 0128–0255 use codepages 850/Windows−1252 for English layout, 866/Windows−1251 for Russian, 737/Windows−1253 for Greek, Windows−1258 for Vietnamese.

Alt-codes can be entered in hexadecimal format: [c]A+0B9[/c] = [c]A+0185[/c] → № (Windows−1251). For this, the input must contain a letter from the A–F range. The upper limit is A+FF (A+255).
[/spoiler2]



[size=150]User-defined bindings[/size]


For creating bindings, you need to place [c]<FILE>.JSON (UTF-8)[/c] in “[c]DSLKeyPad\User\profile-<PROFILE>\CustomBindings\[/c]” with the same structure:


[spoiler2="Details"]

[code=json]
{
  "info": {
    // Preset name
    "name": "Esoteric Binds"
  },
  // Lists of binds, as for single keys
  // and for keys with modifier keys
  "binds": {
    "2:LangFlat": ["digit_2::superscript×20", "digit_1::superscript×10"],
    "A": ["alchemical_brimstone", "alchemical_brimstone_philosophers"],
    "<^>!A": "alchemical_brimstone_black",
    "<^>!B": ["astrological_proserpina"],
    ">+A:Caps": ["astrological_neptune", "astrological_uranus"],
    "<^>!И": ["astrological_chiron"],
    "<^>!Y": [
      "@ඞʂ🍋",
      "@Сижу за решёткой в темнице сырой.\nВскормленный в неволе орёл молодой,\n…"
    ]
  }
}
[/code]

	User-defined bindings supports the following formats:

[code=json]
		// “Flat” (for all languages)
		<"MODIFIER?KEY">: <"VAL">
		// For a specific language
		<"MODIFIER?KEY">: [<"VAL">]
		// Same as above, but different values for active and inactive CapsLock
		<"MODIFIER?KEY">: [<"VAL">, <"VAL">]
		// “Flat” variant
		<"MODIFIER?KEY:Caps">: [<"VAL">, <"VAL">]
		// Binding where the first variant will refer to the English keyboard layout,
		// and the second to the Russian one
		<"MODIFIER?KEY:LangFlat">: [<"VAL">, <"VAL">]
[/code]

And the following values:

[code=json]
		// Just text
		"@<TEXT>"
		// Reference to an entry in the library
		"<ENTRY NAME>::<VARIANT>×<COUNT>"
[/code]

Details about reference format see in the “Reference format” section.

[b]Note:[/b] for [c]RAlt[/c] you need to use [c]<^>![/c].

After creating a preset, it can be selected in the settings window or after restarting the program, or after pressing the 🔁 button next to the dropdown list in the settings window.

[/spoiler2]



[size=150]User-defined sequences[/size]

You can create/edit custom sequences, called “My Recipes“, in the same way as for bindings or with a dedicated recipe-creation GUI. Custom recipes may contain large multiline text as a result.


[spoiler2="Details"]

The main file is presented in JSON format, “[c]DSLKeyPad\User\profile-<PROFILE>\CustomRecipes.json[/c]”. You can also add additional recipe files in INI (UTF-16 LE) or JSON (UTF-8) formats by placing them in the “[c]DSLKeyPad\User\profile-<PROFILE>\CustomRecipes\[/c]” directory. Recipes from there will be automatically loaded at program startup or when pressing the refresh button in the “My Recipes” window.

Loading sequences from XCompose format files is supported. They must be placed in the “[c]DSLKeyPad\User\profile-<PROFILE>\XCompose\[/c]” directory. The file must end with the “[c].XCompose[/c]” extension.

[b]Note:[/b] Only simple XCompose sequences are supported, such as “[c]<Multi_key> <g> <r> <i> <n> : "😁"[/c]” or “[c]<Multi_key> <U1100> <U1100> : "ᄁ" U1101 # HANGUL CHOSEONG SSANGKIYEOK[/c]”. On first launch, for demonstration purposes, a “demo.XCompose” file is created at the specified path with the sequence “[c]<Multi_key> <0> <0> : "∞"[/c]”.

