[size=150]Search[/size]


[c]LWin + LAlt + F[/c]

As already mentioned — each symbol has a set of “tags”, and they can be quite long. For example, “[c]hellenic small letter omega with psili, perispomeni and ypogegrammeni[/c]” will give the symbol “ᾦ”.


[spoiler2="Details"]

You don't have to enter the full tag — “[c]omeg ps pe yp[/c]” will give the same “ᾦ”. However, the shorter the query, the less precise the result will be. You can enter multiple queries separated by commas:

[list]
[*]“[c]des dee, !des dee, lamb, !lamb[/c]” → “[c]𐐔𐐼Λλ[/c]”
[*]“[c]ref, obe, psms, msps[/c]” → “[c]※÷±∓[/c]”
[/list]

Instead of a tag, you can enter an entry name, for example “[c]hel_c_let_l_lambda[/c]” → “[c]Λ[/c]”.

You can use regular expressions, for example:

[list]
[*][c]fut.*?\s+\S+al[/c]” (searching for a tag with any characters and spaces between fut and al) → “ᚺ” (Hagalaz rune), full tag: “[c]germanic rune elder futhark Hagalaz[/c]”.
[*][c]az$[/c]” (searching for a tag ending with az) → “ᛞ” (Mannaz rune), full tag: “[c]germanic rune elder futhark Mannaz[/c]”.
[*][c]^фра[/c]” (searching for a tag starting with фра) → “₣” (Franc).
[/list]

Specifying glyph variations is also supported by adding [c]::<VARIANT>[/c] at the end of the query:

[list]
[*]“[c]lig ae, lig ae::smallCapital, !latin h::fraktur[/c]” → “[c]Æᴁ𝔥[/c]”
[/list]

In addition to symbol search, the query input window supports calling some methods/functions:

[list]
[*][c]\[/c] or [c]/Reload[/c] — restarts the program.
[*][c]/Exit[/c] — closes the program.
[*][c]/ChrLib.Print[/c] — creates and opens a “[c]printed_pairs.html[/c]” file with a listing of local library entries in “symbol — entry name” format.
[*][c]/MyRecipes.Update[/c] — re-initializes user recipes.
[*][c]/Update.Get[/c] or [c]/Update.Repair[/c] — get an update or repair the current version.
[*][c]%globalInstances.crafter.Start("Compose")%[/c] — similar to RAlt×2, activates composition mode…
[*][c]/KbdBinder.Init[/c] — re-initializes layouts and bindings.
[/list]

